04960nam a22006135i 9780520913301DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t19911991cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209133017 a10.1525/97805209133012doi  a(DE-B1597)521078  a(OCoLC)44965882  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD8728b.G65 1991 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a322/.2/0952090412201 aGordon, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLabor and Imperial Democracy in Prewar Japan /cAndrew Gordon. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTwentieth Century Japan: The Emergence of a World Power ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables, Graphs, and Maps -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Movement for Imperial Democracy -- t2. The Urban Crowd and Politics, 1905-18 -- t3. Labor Disputes and the Working Class in Tokyo -- t4. Building a Labor Movement:: Nankatsu Workers and the Yūaikai -- t5. Imperial Democracy as a Structure of Rule -- t6. Nuclei of the Workers' Movement -- t7. The Labor Offensive in Nankatsu, 1924-29 -- t8. Working-Class Political Culture under Imperial Democracy -- t9. The Depression and the Workers' Movement -- t10. The Social Movement Transformed, 1932-35 -- t11. Imperial Fascism, 1935-40 -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. Public Assemblies in Tokyo, 18831938 -- tAppendix B. Victims of the Kameido Incident, September 4, 1923 -- tBibliographic Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLabor and Imperial Democracy in Prewar Japan examines the political role played by working men and women in prewar Tokyo and offers a reinterpretation of the broader dynamics of Japan's prewar political history. Gordon argues that such phenomena as riots, labor disputes, and union organizing can best be understood as part of an early twentieth-century movement for "imperial democracy" shaped by the nineteenth-century drive to promote capitalism and build a modern nation and empire. When the propertied, educated leaders of this movement gained a share of power in the 1920s, they disagreed on how far to go toward incorporating working men and women into an expanded body politic. For their part, workers became ambivalent toward working within the imperial democratic system. In this context, the intense polarization of laborers and owners during the Depression helped ultimately to destroy the legitimacy of imperial democracy.Gordon suggests that the thought and behavior of Japanese workers both reflected and furthered the intense concern with popular participation and national power that has marked Japan's modern history. He points to a post-World War II legacy for imperial democracy in both the organization of the working class movement and the popular willingness to see GNP growth as an index of national glory. Importantly, Gordon shows how historians might reconsider the roles of tenant farmers, students, and female activists, for example, in the rise and transformation of imperial democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aLabor disputesxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aLabor disputeszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor movementxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aLabor movementzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical participationxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aPolitical participationzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aRiotsxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aRiotszJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorking classxPolitical activityxHistoryx20th centuryxJapan. 0aWorking classxPolitical activityzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY /